A way out. <br>
Fate takes the blow,<br>
and the sorrow is all they know.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
We broke apart, but not very far. Our foreheads were touching.<br>
“Do you see?” I asked. He nodded and moved away.<br>
“I don’t want to. But I do.”<br>
“I’m going to go. And I don’t want you to say anything until I’m out that door, okay? I don’t want you to run after me. I don’t want you to yell at me. I’m not going away forever. I’ll visit, and I’ll write. It is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>nothing</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> like last time.”<br>
